WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.140
&gt;&gt; Presenter: All right, folks. Thanks so
much for coming today. We're very happy to

00:00:04.140 --> 00:00:05.710
have Brendan Boyle with us.

00:00:05.710 --> 00:00:13.799
Brendan Boyle is partner and Chief Invention
Officer at IDEO. His role has a special emphasis

00:00:13.799 --> 00:00:17.720
on entrepreneurship, and is focused on creating
intellectual property that IDEO develops,

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:22.670
while promoting entrepreneurial thinking and
practices throughout IDEO's eight global offices.

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:27.570
Before coming to IDEO, Brendan co-founded
a company called Skyliners, which was acquired

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:34.210
by IDEO. And under its leadership, IDEO has
licensed over 125 toy game and consumer products

00:00:34.210 --> 00:00:39.899
with leading manufacturers And in 2007, Crainium
Sounds by the Seashore, which was designed

00:00:39.899 --> 00:00:44.379
by IDEO, was nominated for Toy of the Year
Award by Toy Industry Foundation.

00:00:44.379 --> 00:00:50.230
In addition to his duties at IDEO, Brendan
sits on the board at the non-profit National

00:00:50.230 --> 00:00:55.229
Institute for Play, where focus on bringing
play based techniques to innovation. And currently,

00:00:55.229 --> 00:01:01.399
he teaches a class that he created in Stanford's
new D school, called "From Play to Innovation".

00:01:01.399 --> 00:01:05.570
So we're excited to have Brendan here to talk
about his new book, "The Klutz Book of Inventions".

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:10.110
And he asks if you already bought a book,
please don't start reading it until after

00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:11.110
the talk.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:14.870
So please join me in welcoming Brendan Boyle.

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:15.870
[applause]

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:20.131
&gt;&gt;Brendan Boyle: All right. Thank you.

00:01:20.131 --> 00:01:26.680
So I always like to start a talk with a little
warm-up exercise. And this is one where, if

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:31.260
you're sitting down, pick up your right foot
and spin it in a clockwise motion. Keep spinning

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:36.720
it. And keep spinning it as you draw a big
number six in front of your face. Keep spinning

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:43.520
it clockwise. It's really hard to do, isn't
it? All right. So figure that one out.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.460
So thanks again. This is neat to be here.

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:52.660
So imagine...this book is all around 'Brilliant
meets Ridiculous'. And I'll emphasize that

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:53.660
theme.

00:01:53.660 --> 00:02:00.070
But imagine it's 1887. And you're F. A. Mulleroff.
And you've invented this thing called a contact

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:01.070
lens.

00:02:01.070 --> 00:02:02.270
So any contact lens wearers out there?

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:08.060
And no one's ever seen it before. And you've
prototyped this little piece of blown glass.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:14.160
And you walk up to your friend and say: "Hey
will you test this thing? Put this piece of

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.730
glass in your eye." And friend would say,
"Well, will it break?"

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:23.980
Then you'd say: 'Well, I'm not really sure.
Maybe. But it's probably pretty safe." Your

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:26.230
friend might say, "That's ridiculous! I'm
not gonna try that."

00:02:26.230 --> 00:02:31.340
To me, almost every great invention I think
you could trace back, and someone or a group

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:35.111
of people, or maybe hundreds of people would
say that was a ridiculous idea.

00:02:35.111 --> 00:02:43.480
Or further along the lines of eyewear. Imagine
you're Salvino Damarte. And it's 1284. And

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:49.291
you've invented the first pair of glasses.
And you test them. You put them on someone

00:02:49.291 --> 00:02:53.400
and they say, "I can see better. That's neat.
But aren't I gonna look kinda dorky if I walk

00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:54.520
around with these things?"

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:58.120
For those who wear glasses -- I don't know
about the rest of you. But the first time

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:01.520
I had to wear glasses, I was really worried
about going to school. Like this is gonna

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:06.490
look crazy, right? People are gonna think
I'm different. And so I suspect this seemed

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:08.650
quite a bit, at a time, ridiculous.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:14.870
So think about some of your own big ideas.
Have you heard...has that felt like that's

00:03:14.870 --> 00:03:15.870
ridiculous?

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:22.081
And then one more on the eye care, which would
be laser surgery, which has been around now

00:03:22.081 --> 00:03:27.120
I think thirty some years, in different forms.
But I remember the first time I heard about

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:31.270
this, and I was thinking, "You're gonna shoot
lasers in my eye and then I'm gonna see better?".

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:33.730
That probably seemed like a pretty far out
there idea.

00:03:33.730 --> 00:03:39.950
And I always used to wonder being in California,
"What if you're getting laser surgery and

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:45.480
the earthquake hits?" Like, that would probably
be tricky.

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:49.930
So insert any big invention here. Probably
one of the biggest inventions is the wheel.

00:03:49.930 --> 00:03:54.349
And you could go back a zillion years ago.
And probably the first person fooling around,

00:03:54.349 --> 00:03:57.470
the first cave-person fooling around with
the wheel. The rest of the cave-folks were

00:03:57.470 --> 00:04:01.069
probably thinking. "That's some kind of little
nitwit off to side, doing some type of invention

00:04:01.069 --> 00:04:07.129
thing." Again it's that pushing yourself,
and having a safe enough environment to do

00:04:07.129 --> 00:04:08.129
that.

00:04:08.129 --> 00:04:15.239
&gt;&gt;Music

00:04:15.239 --> 00:04:35.020
&gt;&gt;Brendan Boyle: So John Cassidy and I, John
Cassidy is the founder of Klutz. Great guy.

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:40.020
We decided to push this thinking into a project.
And my whole life's around projects which

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:42.780
I enjoy doing. And he's a great person to
collaborate with.

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:46.930
So we thought, "Why don't we make a whole
bunch of inventions, make a book about it,

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:51.720
which pushes this razor-thin line between
brilliant and ridiculous. Is it a brilliant

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:54.060
idea, or is it a ridiculous one?"

00:04:54.060 --> 00:05:00.030
This is the one on the cover. So just be prepared.
I'm gonna show you a bunch of brilliant meets

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:04.690
ridiculous ideas today. This is the one on
the, the cover, which I wonder if for those

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:08.030
who fly a lot, which I do. And you have to
check your orange juice and you can't bring

00:05:08.030 --> 00:05:11.740
it through TSA. If you would be allowed to
carry this and a bag of oranges, if that would

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:14.960
be okay. You could make that.

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:19.220
So we had -- the project lasted about a year.
We probably could have done it faster. We

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:25.150
ended up building 162. Each one was prototyped
in the shop, built, and then photographed.

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:27.430
And then a story written about it.

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:32.370
We did probably a 100 different brainstorms,
thousands of different ideas. And what we

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:36.729
did to figure out what was that fine line,
was we took the sketches of the ideas to fourth

00:05:36.729 --> 00:05:41.300
and fifth grade classrooms. If they thought
it could be a real idea, like they believed

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:44.991
in it, then that kind of passed that line
about that "Hmm. There's something on that

00:05:44.991 --> 00:05:45.991
fine line."

00:05:45.991 --> 00:05:50.520
There's something about a fourth grader that's
still very child-like but still exposed to

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:55.610
enough adult things. So they've -- they see
a lot of potential, where I worry as we get

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:59.050
older, we start to... we've heard "that can't
be done" enough.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:03.550
So this was reaffirming. I showed this. I
was giving a talk and there was a fifth grader

00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:07.080
in the audience. And during the questions,
he raised his hand and said, "Can I buy that

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:08.080
invention?"

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:09.080
[audience laughter]

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:14.430
And I said, "Dude, I can tell you how to make
one." So, it was pretty neat around that.

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:18.009
So I'm going to distill this down into five
ways to think about being more innovative.

00:06:18.009 --> 00:06:22.960
That's what we do a lot at IDEO, think about
ways to innovate in our process. So I'll talk

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.949
about five of them. A lot these you've probably
heard. So think about ones that you haven't,

00:06:26.949 --> 00:06:31.440
or how you can improve in your own innovation
process.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:36.190
So the first is, I love to, again this whole
premise of encourage your ridiculous. How

00:06:36.190 --> 00:06:39.919
do you get more comfortable? It's really one
is -- there are two things.

00:06:39.919 --> 00:06:43.889
One, you're worried about being judged by
others, being judged by the tribe. "Hey, if

00:06:43.889 --> 00:06:46.900
I throw out this big idea, someone's gonna
say I'm an idiot, or it looks stupid."

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:51.970
Or probably even more dangerous is being judged
by yourself. You'll be in a meeting and you'll

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:56.590
hold back on that idea because you're "Ahh-I
don't know. Maybe it's just not good enough".

00:06:56.590 --> 00:07:01.630
So I think that if you can get more comfortable,
through encouraging ridiculous, and one of

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:03.990
the best ways I know to do that is through
play.

00:07:03.990 --> 00:07:09.242
The reason we like to play is because it's
fun and we wanna do it again. That's the reason

00:07:09.242 --> 00:07:12.320
the dog brings the ball back. "It was enjoyable.
I wanna do it again", right?

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:16.710
So find something that's enjoyable. Then do
it again, and encourage that. So for me around

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:20.430
innovation, that's really neat.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:24.700
So, I'll slice through some ideas in the book
here.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:33.860
So, how might we get in shape while on the
go? So how 'bout the idea of the elevator

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:38.410
with a built-in Stairmaster? So, yeah you
gotta take a hundred flights up, but you gotta

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:39.490
get a little exercise.

00:07:39.490 --> 00:07:46.889
So, maybe this is borderline more on the ridiculous.
But either so much in this country, worldwide

00:07:46.889 --> 00:07:50.520
even, spreading around obesity. I think there's
gonna be a lot more of how do you get people

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:51.729
to move.

00:07:51.729 --> 00:07:56.380
I fly a lot, and I'm always amazed. I'll take
a six-hour cross country trip. People get

00:07:56.380 --> 00:08:01.410
off that plane. They've been sitting and then
they get on that moving sidewalk at SFO. Like,

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:04.750
dude! You could walk. You could get a little
stretching, right? So I think there are going

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:08.389
to be a lot of things around how to get people
to move with this.

00:08:08.389 --> 00:08:10.830
[pause]

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:14.970
All right. For those with kids, how might
we invent a kid's tricycle that does some

00:08:14.970 --> 00:08:16.699
of your yardwork? How to get the kid working
kind of a little bit?

00:08:16.699 --> 00:08:25.770
So I love the lawnmower tricycle. It's got
a few safety concerns. I'll grant you that.

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:32.120
But some proper shrouding, and I think we
could handle that. So this idea probably seems

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:33.130
closer to the ridiculous.

00:08:33.130 --> 00:08:40.610
But I think it was two years ago, Fisher Price
came out with a smart cycle, which is a little

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:45.399
video gaming system. But the kid has to put
some energy in to get some excitement out

00:08:45.399 --> 00:08:47.480
kind of thing, which has done really well
for them.

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:52.240
So again, you'll see, I think a lot more of
thinking around how to get people to move

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:56.230
a little bit.

00:08:56.230 --> 00:09:00.310
So when I think about the innovation process,
we talk a lot about design thinking at IDEO,

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:04.589
we really start with observe and understand.
Understand what the user's doing, that frames

00:09:04.589 --> 00:09:08.899
up into a point of view, into some type of
synthesis, a strategy.

00:09:08.899 --> 00:09:12.589
I'm really focusing around the ideation. So
once we've done that part, how do you push

00:09:12.589 --> 00:09:14.290
yourself to get something more innovative?

00:09:14.290 --> 00:09:20.170
So this book is focused around that. After
that, lots of prototype and testing. And then

00:09:20.170 --> 00:09:25.580
go back and do it again. So what are your
different techniques to ideate more, is really

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:32.260
kind of the focus. Just put in some process
prospective.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:34.670
All right. How might we reinvent the common
parking ticket?

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:38.450
I don't know about you guys, but my office
is downtown Palo Alto. I walk out and I get

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:41.500
a parking ticket. I'm pretty bummed out for
a little bit. Like, "Duh. If I just got here

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:44.140
ten minutes earlier, I could've moved my car".

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:51.360
So we were trying to think how we could reinvent
that. Put the fun back in traffic citations.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:52.360
[audience laughs]

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:56.240
So I get my ticket and you scratch-off: "Double
my fine." "Zero fine." Or "We owe you the

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:57.240
fine!"

00:09:57.240 --> 00:09:58.240
[audience laughs]

00:09:58.240 --> 00:10:02.080
So – and I was talking to someone from the
city of Palo Alto, and they're saying the

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:06.120
biggest problem in parking tickets is people
throw them away. They just don't...especially

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:07.520
if they're from out of town.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:11.500
If you put some fun, you felt like you got
a deal, you'd have to, I think, tweak the

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:16.390
economics here. "I got a dollar off". Maybe
people would feel more apt to pay something

00:10:16.390 --> 00:10:22.160
on that. But this one, I think's closer. I
like this.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:23.560
[pause]

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:30.390
All right. And then another one is: How might
we make using the umbrella easier? How about

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:36.140
if we had the helium umbrella? So, it floats
over your head. It's always something to do

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:37.140
with your arms.

00:10:37.140 --> 00:10:42.791
All right. So I'm gonna...I love a little
warm-up exercise, I need you to pick a partner.

00:10:42.791 --> 00:10:46.980
And you each get a post-it and a pen. And
it doesn't have to be somebody you know. It

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:48.070
can be meet someone new.

00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:52.440
And this'll just take about two or three minutes
to do this exercise. So pick a partner, and

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:57.450
this will encourage a little play. So it's
fine. We'll do a little play here.

00:10:57.450 --> 00:11:03.092
[sounds of audience choosing partners]

00:11:03.092 --> 00:11:04.092
[pause]

00:11:04.092 --> 00:11:06.920
All right. So everyone's got a partner. This
is called, this is called a "Mash Up." One

00:11:06.920 --> 00:11:11.160
person. The first part of the exercise you
do by yourself. So, one person list five things

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:14.860
you would find in your junk drawer, or your
kitchen or your garage. Make them unique.

00:11:14.860 --> 00:11:19.180
Think about five things. The other person.
List five things you'd find in a drugstore.

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:20.180
That's the first part.

00:11:20.180 --> 00:11:25.330
All you need to do is take a minute. Do a
quick list. Decide who is doing what, and

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:26.330
make a quick list.

00:11:26.330 --> 00:11:33.500
[pause]

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:49.690
All right. Play along a little bit.

00:11:49.690 --> 00:11:51.790
[pause]

00:11:51.790 --> 00:12:04.600
Drugstore: Walmart, Walgreens or CVS, Long's,
that kind of thing.

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:06.029
[pause]

00:12:06.029 --> 00:12:09.420
All right. Just another couple seconds to
make your list.

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:13.120
[pause]

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:21.041
You guys are doing well.

00:12:21.041 --> 00:12:22.890
[pause]

00:12:22.890 --> 00:12:32.370
Hey. Okay. All right. Now, take...look at
your lists together over the next--this is

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:37.561
called a "Mash Up". Over the next couple minutes,
see if you can brainstorm a combo idea.

00:12:37.561 --> 00:12:41.120
Here's my example: I've got a welcome mat.
I've got a whoopee cushion. I have a whoopee

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:42.550
mat. Right?

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:47.790
So, do a brainstorm combo idea and push your
thinking. This is "encourage ridiculous".

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:57.990
We're in a safe environment here, and let's
see what we can come up with.

00:12:57.990 --> 00:13:12.550
[audience chatter]

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:19.830
[pause]

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:31.370
All right. If you can do a quick sketch, that's
even better. If you can do a quick sketch,

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:32.370
you guys will rock.

00:13:32.370 --> 00:13:41.430
